The federal government says it will bring the full wrath of the law to bear on employers who violate the rights of their employees under the guise of the COVID-19 pandemic. Minister of Labour and Employment, Dr. Chris Ngige handed out the threat while speaking at a webinar organised by the Abuja Office of the ILO on the impact of COVID-19 on the rights of migrant workers in Nigeria. Dr Ngige says it was wrong for employers to cut the salaries of employees or terminate their appointments without holding negotiations with them to see reason why such measures had become inevitable. “We got report of three states that did this and we have called them to revert and do the right thing,” the minister said. While calling on the Nigerian Employers Consultative Forum, NECA, to report erring employers to his ministry, the labour minister also announced plans to review licences of labour outsourcing firms to ensure that workers are not exposed to indecent work conditions. He denied reports that  COVID-19 palliatives were given to portfolio firms instead of genuine employers of  labour, adding that interventions by the Central Bank of  Nigeria, Bank of Industry, Federal Mortgage Bank of Nigeria, SMEDAN, etc, were given to known and functional business entities. Ngige further expressed concern that over 60 percent of the labour force was in the informal sector, saying  that there was the need to formalize their activities so that they can be captured for any government interventions. Earlier, director-general of NECA, Dr. Timothy Olawale, represented by Mr. Wale Smart, had urged employers not to consider lay-offs and salary cuts as an immediate option to cope with the negative impact of COVID-19. Also speaking,  the general secretary, Nigerian Labour Congress, Emmanuel Ugboaja, emphasised the need to protect the rights of migrant workers and to carry them along in palliative measures to cushion the impact of COVID-19.